<p>
I am currently working on new project to develop interactive web-based educational toos. 
I have started with this simple one, which is an animated version of a famous cartoon of
the standard model of particle physics (see picture above taken from 
<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_Model">wikipedia</a>.  It depicts the fundamental 
particles in the standard model and some of their properties.  This diagram leaves out a 
few aspects of the standard model which, I think, could be incorporated.  
</p>
<p>
The first is the addition of the Higgs boson.  Since we know that something must break electroweak
symmetry, and the Higgs is the simplest case, this should be considered as part of the
picture. 
</p>
<p>
Second, the interactions are left out.  I think in the vein of an interactive diagram, 
one could simply highight the particles that gauge bosons interact with.  This could even
be taken as far as drawing all of the possible primitive tree level feynman diagrams.  
</p>
<p>
A working version of these developments can be found 
<a href="http://www.pha.jhu.edu/~whitbeck/standardModel.html">here</a>.
</p>

